<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910124-0076</DOCNO><DOCID>910124-0076.</DOCID><HL>   Saudis Turn Oil Importer   To Fuel Allied Operations</HL><DATE>01/24/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3</SO><CO>   MDEST C.SRM</CO><IN>PETROLEUM (PET)INTERNATIONAL TRADE NEWS (TRD)</IN><GV>DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)</GV><LP>   MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) -- Saudi Arabia, the world's biggestoil exporter, is importing oil products to fuel OperationDesert Storm.   Allied warplanes have flown more than 12,000 missionssince combat began, some by aircraft that burn their weightin jet fuel on a single mission.</LP><TEXT>   U.S. military officials, citing security reasons, wouldnot say yesterday how much fuel is being used by OperationDesert Storm. But a London-based oil analyst estimated thatthe aircraft are using about 40,000 barrels to 50,000 barrelsof jet fuel daily.   Other analysts have put it even higher, at several hundredthousand barrels daily.   All oil refineries are operating at capacity in the Gulfto process enough jet fuel, diesel and gasoline for theplanes, tanks and other vehicles in the 28-nation alliedforce.   The Saudi state refining company, the Saudi ArabianMarketing andamp; Refining Co., has cut off exports to meet thedemands of Desert Storm.   Oil industry executives say Saudia Arabia has importedeight million barrels of petroleum products since December tomeet the demands of the war effort.   &quot;How much did the Saudis import before? None, zero,&quot; saida Western oil trader in the Gulf.   If a ground war begins, the fuel bill is unlikely toshrink. The M-1 tank uses jet fuel, while the M-60 tank andBradley light tank use diesel, which come from the samerefinery &quot;cut&quot; of petroleum as jet fuel.</TEXT></DOC>